// MARK: - Glossary Definitions
"glossary_def_zero_knowledge_proof" = "A cryptographic method where one party can prove to another that a statement is true, without revealing any information beyond the validity of the statement itself. For example, you can prove you're over 18 without showing your exact age or date of birth. This is the core technology that makes Provii Wallet privacy preserving.";
"glossary_def_pedersen_commitment" = "A cryptographic technique that allows you to commit to a value without revealing it. It has two key properties: hiding (no one can see the committed value) and binding (you cannot change the value after committing). In Provii Wallet, your date of birth is stored as a Pedersen commitment, allowing you to prove facts about your age without revealing your actual birth date.";
"glossary_def_range_proof" = "A type of zero knowledge proof that demonstrates a committed value lies within a specific range, without revealing the actual value. Provii Wallet uses range proofs to prove your age exceeds a minimum (such as 18 or 21) without revealing your exact age or date of birth.";
"glossary_def_cryptographic_commitment" = "A way to commit to information that can be revealed and verified later. Like putting a number in a sealed envelope: no one can see inside, and you cannot swap the number after sealing it. Your age credential uses commitments to hide your date of birth while still allowing you to prove facts about your age.";
"glossary_def_digital_signature" = "A cryptographic technique that proves who created or authorised a document, that the document has not been modified since signing, and that the signer cannot deny having signed it. In Provii Wallet, the issuer digitally signs your credential to prove it is authentic and has not been tampered with.";
"glossary_def_proving_key" = "Public cryptographic data needed to generate zero knowledge proofs. It is the same for all users, about 150 to 200 MB in size, and is downloaded once and cached on your device. The app downloads the proving key the first time you perform a verification.";
"glossary_def_homomorphic_encryption" = "A special form of encryption that allows mathematical operations on encrypted data without decrypting it first. Provii Wallet uses homomorphic properties of Pedersen commitments to compare encrypted ages to threshold values and generate range proofs, all without revealing your actual age.";
"glossary_def_privacy_preserving" = "Technology designed from the ground up to minimise data exposure and protect personal information. Provii Wallet uses zero knowledge proofs that reveal only yes or no answers, your date of birth never leaves your device, verifiers learn nothing about your actual age, no tracking or profiling is possible, and each verification is unlinkable to others.";
"glossary_def_credential" = "A cryptographically signed piece of information that proves an attribute about you. In Provii Wallet, your credential contains your date of birth in an encrypted form, stored only on your device, never transmitted to verifiers, and used to generate zero knowledge proofs.";
"glossary_def_issuer" = "A trusted organisation authorised to verify your identity and create digital credentials. This could be a government agency, licensing office, or other trusted institution. The issuer verifies you once in person, checks official documents, creates and signs your digital credential, then helps you store it on your device.";
"glossary_def_trusted_authority" = "An organisation with legal authority to verify identities, following strict identity verification procedures and maintaining high security standards. Examples include government agencies, licensing offices, and passport offices. You must visit a trusted authority in person to receive your initial credential.";
"glossary_def_verifier" = "A website, app, or service that needs to confirm you meet an age requirement. The verifier learns only whether you meet their requirement (yes or no), nothing about your actual age, date of birth, or anything that could identify you.";
"glossary_def_challenge" = "A request from a verifier specifying what needs to be proven (such as over 18), a unique session identifier, and a cryptographic nonce for security. When you scan a QR code from a verifier, you are receiving a challenge. Your wallet then generates a zero knowledge proof in response.";
"glossary_def_verification_key" = "Public cryptographic data that verifiers use to check if a zero knowledge proof is valid. Much smaller than the proving key (about 1 KB), it is public and widely distributed. When a verifier checks your proof, they use the verification key to mathematically confirm it is valid.";
"glossary_def_session" = "A single age verification attempt from start to finish: the verifier creates a challenge, you scan the QR code, the app generates a proof, the proof is submitted, and the verifier checks it. Each session is unique, time-limited, and cannot be reused or replayed.";
"glossary_def_qr_code" = "A square barcode that contains information you can scan with your camera. Provii Wallet uses QR codes for credential issuance (scanning a code from the issuer) and age verification (scanning a code from a verifier). If you have difficulty scanning, you can use manual code entry instead.";
"glossary_def_biometric_authentication" = "Using fingerprint or face recognition to secure your credentials and authorise age proofs.";
"glossary_def_api" = "Application Programming Interface. A way for apps to communicate with each other and with servers.";
"glossary_def_url" = "Uniform Resource Locator. A web address used to locate resources on the internet.";
"glossary_def_id" = "Identification. Proof of who you are, such as a driver's licence or passport.";
"glossary_def_mdl" = "Mobile Driver's Licence. A digital version of your driver's licence stored on your phone.";
"glossary_def_pin" = "Personal Identification Number. A secret numeric code used to protect access to your wallet.";
"glossary_def_provii" = "The name of this wallet application for privacy preserving age verification.";

